    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm a bit stuck on a syntax tree for a sentence in my intro class. If I have the sentence \"The student saw the professor with the telescope,\" I'm seeing two different ways to parse the PP \"with the telescope.\" One version attaches it to the NP \"the professor,\" but my textbook shows it attaching to the VP \"saw.\" Can you explain the structural difference in how those branches are drawn and why the VP attachment is a valid reading?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Attaching \"with the telescope\" to the NP \"the professor\" makes it an adjectival modifier, meaning the telescope describes the professor.  Conversely, attaching it to the VP \"saw\" makes it an adverbial modifier, indicating the instrument used for the seeing action. The VP attachment is valid because it describes *how* the seeing occurred, which is a common function for prepositional phrases in English. This ambiguity is a classic example of structural ambiguity in syntax.",
      "source": "target",
