      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, thanks. So when we're actually drawing these out, the structure becomes much more complex as we add more layers. If I'm looking at the actual tree diagram, how do the branching paths for a VP attachment differ visually from an NP attachment? It gets pretty messy with all the nodes and lines.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Visually, the key difference lies in where the prepositional phrase (PP) branches off from the main constituent nodes. For an NP attachment, the PP will typically be a sister to the head noun within the Noun Phrase structure, often below the Noun (N) node. In contrast, for a VP attachment, the PP will branch off as a sister to the Verb Phrase (VP) itself, often below the Verb (V) node, indicating it modifies the action.",
      "source": "target",
