      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While some structural intuition must be built up through practice, a helpful technique is to always think about the *function* of the phrase first. Ask yourself: is this phrase describing a thing (an NP modifier, like *the professor with the telescope*) or is it describing an action (a VP modifier, like *saw with the telescope*)? Mapping the function before drawing the diagram can keep the structure organized. Another useful method is to use different colors or specific conventions for different types of attachments when you are sketching out complex trees.",
